<P N="137">&sect;. 137. While I thus repre&s;ent what all who knew hi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> mu&s;t &s;oon have ob&s;erved of Colonel Gardiner's affectio<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> regard to the&s;e peculiar doctrines of our holy religion, it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> nece&s;&s;ary that I &s;hould al&s;o inform my reader, that it w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> not his judgment, that the attention of mini&s;ters or th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> hearers &s;hould be wholly ingro&s;&s;ed by the&s;e, excellent <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> they are; but that all the parts of the &s;cheme of truth an<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> duty &s;hould be regarded in their due connection and propor+tion. Far from that di&s;tempered ta&s;te which can bear no|thing but cordials, it was his deliberate judgment, that t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> law &s;hould be preached, as well as the go&s;pel; and hard<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> any thing gave him greater offence, than the irrevere<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> manner in which &s;ome, who have been ignorantly extolle<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> as the mo&s;t zealous and evangelical preachers, have &s;ome+times been tempted to &s;peak of the former; much inde<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> to the &s;candal of all con&s;i&s;tent and judicious chri&s;tians. H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> delighted to be in&s;tructed in his duty, and to hear much <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the inward exerci&s;es of the &s;piritual and divine life. A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> he always wi&s;hed, &s;o far as I could ob&s;erve, to have th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> topics treate